Transgenerational AL/DR Initial Analysis

Katie Evans

03 April, 2018

Introduction

Experimental design: Ryan Baugh Lab grew N2, CB4856, and 65 RIAILs for four days, bleached the population, and split into two groups: AL conditions and DR conditions. A subset of animals were partitioned off and frozen as arrested L1s one day after the bleach. This serves as the baseline population. In both AL and DR conditions, worms were grown for 96 hours, bleached, and split into two groups: in one group, 50,000 animals were recovered for four days and then frozen (D0). In the other group (D8), worms were arrested as L1s for 8 days, then 50,000 animals were recovered for four days. This leaves us with 5 conditions: baseline, AL-D0, AL-D8, DR-D0, and DR-D8. This experiment was performed twice with the worms in the last step being recovered either 1) in liquid or 2) on plates. All ten samples were sequenced.

Experimental Analysis: Katie downloaded the 10 fastq files, aligned them to the N2 reference (WS245) using BWA, called single nucleotide variants using bcftools at the ~175,000 SNVs in CB4856, and quantified the number of REF/ALT reads at each site. Allele counts were saved and uploaded to R for further analysis.

Looking at allele frequency estimations of the 65 RIAILS + N2 + CB4856

Below is the plot for the frequency of the N2 allele in the population of strains used for the experiment, by position. (REF / (REF + ALT)). There is much more variation for the distribution of the REF allele by position in the baseline of the experiments. This is probably due to ratios of low number of reads (mean number of reads at a position is 11.6 for experiment #3 and 21.8 for experiment #4. For this reason, I decided to group SNVs based on their centimorgan position in the RIAILs, sum the REF and ALT alleles for each centimorgan and apply this ratio to each SNV. This resulted in much cleaner baseline allele frequencies that match our expected allele frequencies given the whole-genome sequence data of each RIAIL in the analysis.

Using whole-genome sequence data for each of the 65 RIAILs used in the assay (plus N2 and CB4856 parents), I calculated the number of alleles that should be REF vs ALT at each SNV in the genome. I then calculated the allele frequency ratio (REF / ALT + REF) and compared this ratio to the same ratio calculated experimentally with both baseline from experiment 3 and experiment 4 (grouped by centimorgan, not SNV, as noted above). The correlation between the expected and observed allele frequency ratio for experiment 3 is 0.7221436 and experiment 4 is 0.7277108. Below are histograms plotted to represent the Observed / Expected values of allele frequency ratios. If they are the same we should expect a mean of 1.0. We find a mean of 1.3061421 for experiment 3 and 1.2651668 for experiment 4. Allowing for experimental error, these baseline replicates are very close to matching what we expected in-silico.

Comparing baseline samples between experiments 3 and 4

Below I compare the baseline samples for the two experiments. Ideally, they will be the same their correltation will help us to estimate the experimental error across replicates. Comparing the ratio of REF / total gives us a correlation of 0.9330936.

The histogram below shows the distribution of ratios between baseline_3 / baseline_4 for each variant across the genome. They center around a mean of 1.062977 and a standard deviation of 0.0949558. This is promising because it shows that the majority of ratio of the baselines are similar (average around 1). The red line represents the sample mean and the black line represents the expected mean. A similar shape is seen if you split by chromosome. These results suggest there is little variation among the experiments, so we can compare them.

Conclusions

The baseline allele frequencies line up nicely with what we expected from the in-silico analysis. Additionally, the two experiments are very reproducible. It should be noted that there is a lot of variation if you look SNV by SNV, but grouping the SNVs based on centimorgan distance in the RIAILs allows us to look at the overall pattern and disregard noise likely due to low sequencing depth.

Experiment 3

Analysis Pipeline

  1. Each SNV was grouped by centimorgan and the REF and ALT alleles were summed across all SNVs in that centimorgan group.
  2. Each of the 5 conditions were transformed to a ratio: log2[REF / (REF + ALT)]
    1. This ratio was determined because there are more ALT reads with NA or 0 than REF
  3. Each of the four non-baseline conditions were normalized to baseline (e.g. log2[ALD0 / baseline])
    1. Plots were made to show the normalized allele frequency ratio per variant in each condition.
  4. Ratios of pairwise conditions (after normalizing to baseline) were plotted (e.g. log2[ALD0.norm / ALD8.norm])
  5. Pairwise deltas were calculated to look at the change in allele frequency ratios per variant site across the genome (e.g. log2[ALD0.norm] - log2[ALD8.norm].
    1. Plots were made to show the delta in normalized allele frequency ratios between each pairwise condition

Normalized allele frequencies by condition (log2 transformed)

Below are the plots that show the normalized allele frequency ratio (REF / ALT + REF) for each of the four conditions (ALD0, ALD8, DRD0, and DRD8) by genomic position. The allele frequency was log2 transformed for plotting.

Conclusions

The plots for condition specific QTL look almost identical. The log2 transformed conditions are also very similar, but there are differences. Particularly with DR-D0-3 ALT peak on chrIV at 5 Mb and AL-D8-3 ALT peak at 10 Mb. Lets look at the deltas between conditions next to see if we can isolate these changes.

Normalized deltas of allele frequencies beween conditions (log2 transformed)

Below show the plots for the deltas of each log2 transformed pairwise condition. In each case, the conditions were first normalized by baseline as shown above.

Conclusions

We can observe likely significant QTL marking a change in allele frequency ratios between two pariwise conditions. For example, there seems to be a large peak for ALD0/ALD8 on chrX at 10 Mb that is not found in other pairwise comparisons. Similarly, both DRD0/DRD8 and ALD8/DRD8 show a peak on the far right (15 Mb) of chrI. Finally, a peak is observed for ALD0/DRD0 around 5 Mb on chrIV. We can see a similar pattern looking at the log2 transformed ratios. The most notable addition being ALD0/DRD0 on chrI we can see a stronger peak (although it was also in the raw ratios) around 10 Mb that seems to favor the ALT allele.

Experiment 4

Normalized allele frequencies by condition (log2 transformed)

Below are the plots that show the normalized allele frequency ratio (REF / ALT + REF) for each of the four conditions (ALD0, ALD8, DRD0, and DRD8) by genomic position. The allele frequency was log2 transformed for plotting.

Conclusions

In this experiment, there seems to be some architecture difference between the AL and DR conditions. For example, in the AL conditions, chrX has a broad concave curve peaking around 5 Mb then slowly declining. In contrast, the DR condition chrX is much flatter with maybe more of an “s” shape.

Normalized deltas of allele frequencies beween conditions (log2 transformed)

Below show the plots for the deltas of each log2 transformed pairwise condition. In each case, the conditions were first normalized by baseline as shown above.

Conclusions

I noticed that DRD0/DRD8 seems to be very flat allele frequency across the genome except a few spikes on chrIV and the right of chrI. In contrast, ALD0/DRD0 and ALD8/DRD8 show more variation with SNVs in the chromosome centers to be higher REF alleles than at the arms. Also notice ALD0/ALD8 chrI peaks in opposite directions around 10 Mb.
